<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870428-0059 </DOCNO><HL> Iacocca Says His Pay RoleIs a High-Principled Model</HL><DD> 04/28/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> CAUTOS, AUTO PARTS (AUT) </IN><DATELINE> HIGHLAND PARK, Mich.  </DATELINE><TEXT>   To hear Lee A. Iacocca tell it, it wasn't just the money, it was the principle.    Chrysler Corp.'s blunt-speaking chairman was asked at a news conference yesterday to explain the $20.6 million he received last year in salary, bonuses, stock grants and stock options -- particularly at a time when the auto maker is cutting costs in part by limiting merit pay and other compensation for certain white-collar employees.    &quot;That's the American way,&quot; Mr. Iacocca said of his own compensation. &quot;If little kids don't aspire to make money like I did, what the hell good is this country? You gotta give them a role model, right?&quot; </TEXT></DOC>